ğŸ” Background

The 2025 BMJ article titled "Culture should be a strategic priority amid the changing landscape of the healthcare system" emphasizes the importance of culture in healthcare. However, it lacks a practical method to reconcile conflicting values within organizations.

The SML-CML model addresses this gap by offering a structured approach to align organizational values with on-the-ground practices.

ğŸ§  SML-CML Application

CML (Cosmological Meaning Layer): Represents core organizational worldviews (e.g., prioritizing life extension vs. quality of life).

SML (Semantic Meaning Layer): Structures interpretations and judgments grounded in those values.

In healthcare, for example, a top-down directive may prioritize life extension, while frontline staff may emphasize QOL. This discrepancy reflects a misalignment between CML and SML.

ğŸŒ Case Study

Post-Disaster Value Shift: After the Great East Japan Earthquake, many people reevaluated their life values (Uchida et al., 2014).

This illustrates how shifts in CML (worldview) transform SML (daily decisions and meanings).

âœ… Significance

The SML-CML model provides:

A framework to diagnose why top-down values often fail to reach the ground level

A structure to map and mediate value pluralism within organizations

A practical tool for implementing cultural change and coherence

